Quasar

Lovdip Singh

08/01/2021

Goal of study

To find the ‘best’ model to fit astronomical data associated with measuring quasars (RFWidth).

Read in data

quasar.df <- read.csv('quasar.csv')

pairs20x(quasar.df)

Logging RFWidth is appropriate as it appears to be right skewed from the histogram. Also there appears to be increasing variability when plotted against other variables.

Not all variables may be of use as some have little to no relationship with RFWidth and most other variables, for example redshift. Also some variables do a similar job in explaining RFWidth as other variables.

Model fitting

quasar.fit <- lm(log(RFWidth)~., data=quasar.df)

library(MuMIn)
options(na.action = "na.fail")
all.fits <- dredge(quasar.fit)
## Fixed term is "(Intercept)"
# 5 best fitting models 
all.fits[1:5,]

AICc is a more appropriate measure of model adequacy than AIC for this data as the sample size is quite low (25). Furthermore, \(n / K < 40\) where n is the number of observations and K is the number of parameters, this is true for this case, which makes AICc appropriate (Burnham & Anderson 2002).

The best model is slightly better at supporting the data than the 2nd and 3rd models, as the AICc difference is between 2-4, and is considerably better than the 4th and 5th models (AICc difference between 4-10).

quasar.fit <-  get.models(all.fits, 1)[[1]]

plot(quasar.fit, which=1)

normcheck(quasar.fit)

cooks20x(quasar.fit)

summary(quasar.fit)

The pairwise plot of the variables showed that modeling the log of RFWidth is appropriate and relationships between the variables appeared to be linear. All linear submodels were fitted and the one with lowest AICc was chosen.

The residual plot was fine with extremely small residuals and constant scatter around zero, the normality assumptions were satisfied and there were no unduly influential points. All model assumption were satisfied.

Our final model is:

\[log(RFWidth) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times flux_i + \beta_2 \times line_i + \beta_3 \times luminosity_i + \epsilon_i \] Where \(\epsilon_i \sim iid \space N(0, \sigma^2)\)

Our model explained near all of the variability in the logged RFWidth values.

Executive Summary

# Backtransform
round(exp(confint(quasar.fit)), 3)
##             2.5 % 97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.000  0.000
## flux        2.199  2.314
## line        4.418  4.625
## luminosity  2.510  2.538
100 * (exp(confint(quasar.fit)) - 1)
##                 2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) -100.0000 -100.0000
## flux         119.9322  131.4087
## line         341.7526  362.4621
## luminosity   150.9691  153.7907

We were interested in modeling RFWidth using other variables measured. We found that modeling the log of RFWidth was appropriate in this situation. We found that flux, line and luminosity were the most important variables for explaining the log of RFWidth.

We estimate that on average, if other parameters are constant, each additional unit of:

  • flux results in an increase of RFWidth by between 120% to 131%,
  • line flux results in an increase of RFWidth by between 342% to 362%,
  • luminosity results in an increase of RFWidth by between 151% to 154%.

References

Burnham, K. P. and Anderson, D. R (2002) Model selection and multimodel inference: a practical information-theoretic approach. 2nd ed. New York, Springer-Verlag.
